snippet: Mr. Sanders was met with scorn when he arrived on Capitol Hill in 1990. But in the years since, he has evolved from a gadfly to a reliable team player.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Bernie Sanders was elected to the House in 1990 after branding himself an outsider and defying calls to join a Democratic Party he had long bashed as “ideologically bankrupt.”
abstract: Mr. Sanders was met with scorn when he arrived on Capitol Hill in 1990. But in the years since, he has evolved from a gadfly to a reliable team player.

abstract: Kamala Harris gets a bump after the debates, Pete Buttigieg raises $24.8 million and Cory Booker unveils an immigration overhaul.

snippet: It’s time for lawmakers to step back in, carefully.
lead_paragraph: Tech regulation may be the only thing on which a polarized Capitol Hill can agree. “We should be suing Google and Facebook and all that, and perhaps we will,” President Trump recently declared. Senator Elizabeth Warren, a Democratic presidential candidate, has made the breakup of tech companies a central plank of her campaign. Even Silicon Valley-friendly contenders like Pete Buttigieg have called for curbs on the industry’s power.

snippet: Ms. Harris’s total for the quarter, which went from April through June, is far below what some other first-tier candidates reported this week.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Kamala Harris of California raised less than $12 million in the past three months, her campaign said on Friday, a total that leaves her well behind her top rivals in the Democratic presidential primary’s money race.
abstract: Ms. Harris’s total for the quarter, which went from April through June, is far below what some other first-tier candidates reported this week.

snippet: It’s offensive to both politics and religion.
lead_paragraph: Looking for a new villain to account for the polarization and sheer meanness of our current politics? Instead of blaming deep divisions over race, misogyny, immigration, income inequality and the bellicose Twitter reign of President Trump, many have seized on secularism as a scapegoat for everything that keeps politically conscious and conscientious Americans awake at night.
abstract: It’s offensive to both politics and religion.

headline_main: Stop Calling Politics Our New Religion

snippet: The field of 24 candidates is too unwieldy, some Democrats say. But with big names like the Clintons and Obamas remaining silent, the party lacks anyone to sort it out.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — John Deeth is the sort of Iowa activist who keeps up with every new twist in the Democratic presidential primary, but there was no way he was going to devote two evenings to watching the first round of debates last week.
abstract: The field of 24 candidates is too unwieldy, some Democrats say. But with big names like the Clintons and Obamas remaining silent, the party lacks anyone to sort it out.

headline_main: Democrats Grapple With a Sprawling Primary Field, and No One to Shape It
headline_print_headline: Party Without Leader,  And a Primary Lineup With Too Many Names

snippet: Moving from poverty to wealth from one generation to the next is least likely in the South, but optimism there is greatest, tinged with political views.
lead_paragraph: HUNTSVILLE, Ala. — A widening income gap and sagging social mobility have left dents in the American dream. But the belief that anyone with enough gumption and grit can clamber to the top remains central to the nation’s self-image.
abstract: Moving from poverty to wealth from one generation to the next is least likely in the South, but optimism there is greatest, tinged with political views.

snippet: Tiffany Cabán’s 1,100-vote lead evaporated after the count of paper ballots, putting Melinda Katz 20 votes ahead in the hotly contested primary.
lead_paragraph: [Read the latest on the Queens district attorney race: On Friday, Melinda Katz saw her lead over Tiffany Cabán narrow to 16 votes.]
abstract: Tiffany Cabán’s 1,100-vote lead evaporated after the count of paper ballots, putting Melinda Katz 20 votes ahead in the hotly contested primary.
